# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cleveland-spiders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The **1887 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1887.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 10, with the Detroit Wolverines and the St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Colonels set a Major League record which still stands for the most base on balls for a team in a game, with 19 against the Cleveland Blues on 21 September.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Kansas City Cowboys folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Pittsburgh Alleghenys.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In place of the Alleghenys leaving the AA for the NL, the Cleveland Blues were enfranchised.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons relocated to Indianapolis, Indiana as the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] On July 14, Chicago was to play an exhibition game against the Eastern League Newark team, who were set to play black players Moses Fleetwood Walker (who formerly played in the majors in 1884 three years prior) and George Stovey (who the New York Giants had their eyes on signing).
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] With threats from Chicago to not play against Newark if Walker and Stovey played, they were substituted for the game.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Between Chicago's financial threats to not play against teams with people of color and other minor league teams creating petitions to force teams to release players of color, Organized Baseball effectively set up the baseball color line.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The color line would remain firm for 60 years until the Brooklyn Dodgers called up Jackie Robinson in 1947, breaking the color line.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The process of integration would then last for another 12 years until 1959, when the last major league team, the Boston Red Sox integrated by calling up Pumpsie Green.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams, while each NL team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other seven teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were continued from their implementation the previous season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format the following season, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 16 featuring all eight teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 27, featuring four teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 10 with four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 8, featuring all eight teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 World's Championship Series took place between October 10 and October 26.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 season saw many radical changes which affected the game, as well as unity on rules by the American Association and National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams played in two neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (14 in AA, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Historical statistics for the season were later revised, such that "Bases on balls shall always be treated as neither a time at bat nor a hit for the batter." This results in ambiguity for some players' season and career hits totals, notably with Cap Anson.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Anson was credited with a .421 average and the National League batting title in 1887; however, the recalculation of averages with walks excluded lowered his average to .347 and retroactively gave the batting title to Sam Thompson.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 batting average and hits are included below, using contemporary data on Baseball Reference.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues join the American Association and play at National League Park in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The first structure of the South End Grounds, home of the Boston Beaneaters, would see its last game on September 10, seeing a completely new structure built over the following offseason.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The **1889 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1889.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the New York Giants and the Brooklyn Bridegrooms as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the sixth World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 9 on October 29, in what was a best-of-eleven-playoff.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Dodgers, six games to three, capturing their second consecutive World's Championship Series.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Detroit Wolverines folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Cleveland Blues, renamed to the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] In Cleveland's AA place, the Columbus Solons were enfranchised.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of the NL's Indianapolis Hoosiers & Washington Nationals, and the AA's Kansas City Cowboys.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the previous season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring four teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 24, featuring all eight teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with four teams playing, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5, featuring all eight teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 29.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Initial version of stadium burned in a fire in mid-May and was rebuilt in time before the need for a neutral site.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (13 in AA, 13 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Columbus Solons join the American Association and play at Recreation Park in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following their eviction from the original Polo Grounds in New York, New York over the offseason, the New York Giants would play at several ballparks while waiting for their next home further uptown, also called the Polo Grounds, to finish construction.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at Oakland Park in Jersey City, New Jersey for two games on April 24 and 25, before beginning play at the St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] George, New York, the former home of the New York Metropolitans, where they played from April 29 through June 14.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following a road trip, the team would begin play at the new Polo Grounds on July 8.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] A fire at Washington Park, home of the Brooklyn Bridegrooms occurred on May 17 while the team was on a road trip.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The burnt down grandstand and fencing were rebuilt in time for the team to play their next scheduled home game, on May 30.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The **Cleveland Spiders** were an American professional baseball team based in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The team competed at the major league level from 1887 to 1899, first for two seasons as a member of the now-defunct American Association (AA), followed by eleven seasons in the National League (NL).
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Early names for the team included the **Forest Citys** and **Blues**.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The name Spiders itself emerged early in the team's inaugural NL season of 1889, owing to new black-and-gray uniforms and the skinny, long-limbed look of many players (thereby resembling the spider).
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] National League Park served as the team's home for its first four seasons until the opening of League Park in 1891.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Amid seven straight winning seasons under manager Patsy Tebeau, the team finished second in the National League three times – in 1892, 1895, and 1896.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] While the Spiders never won the National League pennant, the club did win the 1895 Temple Cup, a two-team league championship playoff predating the World Series.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders beat that year's pennant winner, the Baltimore Orioles (unrelated to the modern franchise), four games to one in a best-of-seven game series.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Six Spiders players were later inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, including left fielder Jesse Burkett and pitcher Cy Young.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, owners Frank and Stanley Robison purchased a second team – the bankrupt St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Louis NL franchise – and sent all of the Spiders' top talent to that club, including future Hall-of-Famers Young, Burkett, and Bobby Wallace.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The resulting Spiders roster finished the 1899 season 20–134, a record which remains the worst for a single season in major league history.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were subsequently one of four teams contracted by the National League that year.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Partly in response to the Robison brothers' actions – which effectively ended the Spiders franchise – the practice of "syndicate ownership" was later banned.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis played for the team during its final three seasons and is often credited as the first Native American to play major league baseball.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians, major league successor to the Spiders in Cleveland, have long cited Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – though that claim is disputed.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were the third professional baseball franchise based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The first team, Forest City, which played from 1870 through 1872, was initially an independent team before joining the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for two seasons before disbanding.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] They were followed in 1879 by the city's first National League team, the Cleveland Blues, which folded after the 1884 season.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] After the 1886 season, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys left the American Association (AA) to join the National League.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The AA, then considered a major league, chose the Cleveland group headed by Frank Robison as an expansion team to begin play in 1887 over proposals from Kansas City and Detroit.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Later, Robison's brother Stanley was added to the ownership group.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Initially, the team was known as the Forest Citys, drawing on the city's nickname and the nickname that had been used on the city's two previous professional baseball teams.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The nickname Blues was also used again in reference to the team uniforms.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Forest Citys were a weak team in their early years.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1889, they moved to the National League and became known as the Spiders, reportedly after comments from a team executive assessing the players.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Brunell, this team executive who also doubled as sportswriter for *The Plain Dealer*, noted the combination of the team's new black-and-gray uniforms together with the sight of several skinny, long-limbed players.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] He joked the team should be called "Spiders", and the name stuck.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The team started to improve in 1891, largely due to the signing of future Baseball Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders had their first taste of success in 1892 when they finished 93–56 overall; winning the second half by three games over Boston with a 53–23 record.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Other than standout second baseman Cupid Childs, the Spiders had an unremarkable offense.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Their success in 1892 was built on pitching strength; Cy Young was the NL's most dominant hurler, and 22-year-old George Cuppy had an outstanding rookie year.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Following the season, a "World's Championship Series" exhibition was played between Cleveland and the first-half winner Boston Beaneaters, but the Spiders could only muster one tie in six games.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1895, the Spiders again finished second, this time to the equally rough-and-tumble Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Young again led the league in wins, and speedy left fielder Jesse Burkett won the batting title with a .409 average.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders won the Temple Cup, an 1890s postseason series between the first- and second-place teams in the NL.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Amid fan rowdyism and garbage-throwing, the Spiders won four of five games against Baltimore, including two wins for Cy Young.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The 1895 championship was the high-water mark for the franchise.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The following season, Baltimore and Cleveland again finished first and second in the NL, but in the battle for the 1896 Temple Cup, the second-place Spiders were swept in four games.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1897, despite a winning record, the franchise finished fifth, a season highlighted by Young throwing the first of three career no-hitters on September 18.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders again finished fifth in 1898.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, the Spiders' owners, the Robison brothers, bought the St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Louis Browns out of bankruptcy and changed their name to the Perfectos.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] However, they kept the Spiders as well—a blatant conflict of interest.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Believing the Perfectos would draw greater attendance in more densely populated St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Louis, the Robisons transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Baseball Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, to St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] They also shifted a large number of Cleveland home games to the road (for instance, the original Opening Day game was shifted to St.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] With a decimated roster, the Spiders made a wretched showing.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] They finished with a dismal win-loss record of 20–134 (.130), the worst in MLB history, 84 games behind the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas and 35 games behind the next-to-last (11th) place Washington Senators.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Their batting records were the worst in the league in runs, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, walks, stolen bases, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons announced after buying the Perfectos that they intended to run the Spiders as a "sideshow", and Cleveland fans apparently took them at their word.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders' first 16 home games drew a total of 3,179 fans, or an average of 199 fans per game.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Due to these meager attendance figures, the other 11 NL teams refused to come to League Park, as their cut of the revenue from ticket sales did not even begin to cover their hotel and travel expenses.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were thus forced to play 85 of their remaining 93 games on the road.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Counting the large number of home games that had been shifted to the road earlier in the season, they only played 42 home games during the season, including only eight after July 1, and finished 9–33 (.214) at home and 11–101 (.098) on the road.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Only 6,088 fans paid to attend Spiders home games in 1899, for a pitiful average of a mere 145 spectators per game in 9,000-seat League Park.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The 101 road losses is a major-league record that will never be threatened, as current scheduling practices have teams play a maximum of 81 away games.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20–21.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The 1962 New York Mets, 40–120 (.250), and the 2024 Chicago White Sox, 41–121 (.253), own the modern records in their respective leagues for the most losses, and thus draw frequent comparisons to the 1899 Spiders for futility.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons' decision to effectively reduce the Spiders to minor league status, along with other intra-league raiding such as that conducted by the Dodgers and to a lesser extent the Pittsburgh Pirates, unwittingly helped pave the way to the National League's loss of its major league monopoly.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The 12th-place Spiders were one of four teams contracted out of the National League at the end of the 1899 season (the others were the 11th-place Senators, the ninth-place Louisville Colonels and the bankrupt fourth-place Baltimore Orioles).
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The 1899 fiasco played a role in the major leagues passing a rule which barred one person from owning controlling interest in two clubs.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons sold the assets of the Spiders team to Charles Somers and John Kilfoyle in 1900.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1900, the then-minor American League (previously the Western League) moved the Grand Rapids (baseball) team in to take the Spiders' place, and called the Cleveland Lake Shores.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] In 1901, after the American League declared major league status, the team was called the Cleveland Blues, eventually the Cleveland Indians, and now the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians have long claimed Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – in use from 1915 to 2021.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] Sockalexis played three seasons for the Cleveland Spiders, from 1897 to 1899, and is often credited as the first Native American to play professional baseball at the major league level.
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] During his time with the Spiders, the press often referred to the team as the Indians or "Tebeau's Indians".
[src:cleveland-spiders/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians claim has been disputed, however, including in a 2012 *Cleveland Scene* essay titled "The Curse of Chief Wahoo", which argues the organization cited Sockalexis in part to justify use of the "Indians" name.
